i, but is currently and permanently considered part of Taguig. A 2003 ruling by a judge in the Pasig Regional Trial Court has upheld the jurisdiction of Taguig over the whole of Fort Bonifacio, including Barangay Pinagsama and Bonifacio Global City.\n\n===Ruling===\nThe Supreme Court on June 27, 2008 per [[Leonardo Quisumbing]], dismissed the suit of the [[Makati]], seeking to nullify Special Patents 3595 and 3596 signed by [[Fidel Ramos]] conveying to the [[Bases Conversion and Development Authority]] public land in [[Fort Bonifacio]], Taguig. Because of a pending civil case filed by the Taguig City government asking the court to define its territorial boundaries, Makati therefore cannot stop Taguig from collecting taxes on land located in Fort Bonifacio.<ref>[http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/?page=police2_june30_2008 Court junks Makati's suit to nullify Ramos patents], manilastandardtoday.com; accessed August 10, 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.supremecourt.gov.ph/jurisprudence/2008/june2008/163175.htm Binay v Taguig, G.R. No. 163175, June 27, 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080710102645/http://www.supremecourt.gov.ph/jurisprudence/2008/june2008/163175.htm |date=July 10, 2008 }}, supremecourt.gov.ph; accessed August 10, 2015.</ref> Taguig is competing with Makati, where round-the-clock construction of office and residential towers, as well as hotels and retail and commercial areas, BPO and call centers, are now transferring to Taguig.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n===Court of Appeals decisions===\nOn August 5, 2013, the Court of Appeals declared almost the entire Fort Bonifacio, parts of Barangay Western Bicutan and parts of Barangay Pinagsama are under the territorial jurisdiction of Makati<ref>[http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/320707/news/nation/ca-fort-bonifacio-under-makati Court of Appeals declares Fort Bonifacio, parts of Western Bicutan and parts of Pinagsama as part of Makati City], gmanetwork.com; accessed August 10, 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.rappler.com/nation/35667-fort-bonifacio-makati-boundary-dispute Fort Bonifacio-Makati dispute], rappler.com; accessed August 10, 2015.</ref>\n\n===Status Quo prevails===\n[[File:Fort Bonifacio 2.JPG|thumb|right|The district of [[Fort Bonifacio]]]]\nOn August 22, 2013, Taguig filed a Motion for Reconsideration before the Court of Appeal's Sixth Division affirming its claim on Fort Bonifacio.<ref>[http://www.taguig.gov.ph/taguig-reaffirms-claim-over-fort-bonifacio Taguig reaffirms claim over Fort Bonifacio], taguig.gov.ph; accessed August 10, 2015.</ref>\n\n\"Taguig's claim has the backing of history\u2014it precedes Makati as a political and corporate entity by decades. Taguig's claim has the weight of official authority behind it\u2014in statutes, in proclamations, in public documents\u2014while Makati can only rely on private writings and proclamations that expand the original terms of that which it sought to amend\", part of the motion read.\n\n\"Taguig's claim has been established by the numerous documentary and official documents, while Makati's has been one characterized by numerous legal maneuvers and overreliance on technicalities\", the motion added. With the filing of the said Motion for Reconsideration, Taguig's jurisdiction forces itself over Fort Bonifacio. According to Taguig's legal department, jurisprudence and the rules of procedure in the country's justice system all say that the filing of a motion for reconsideration suspends the execution of a decision and puts it in limbo.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n===Supreme Court's 2nd Decision===\nOn August 1, 2016, in a 27-page decision by the Second Division of the Supreme Court, the decision sought Makati government found guilty of direct contempt for abusing the legal processes over the jurisdiction of BGC.<ref>{{cite news|title=Makati guilty of direct contempt over BGC row with Taguig|last=Torres-Tupas|first=Tetch|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/801669/makati-guilty-of-direct-contempt-over-bgc-row-with-taguig|newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=August 1, 2016|accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Final decision===\nOn October 3, 2017, the Court of Appeals upheld its final decision in favor of Taguig City government and not Makati. The SC also sought Makati guilty of forum shopping after simultaneously appealing the Pasig RTC ruling and filing a petition before the CA, both seeking the same relief.<ref>{{cite news|title=CA: Taguig owns BGC, not Makati|last=Ramos|first=Marlon|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/943180/ca-taguig-owns-bgc-not-makati|newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=November 6, 2017|accessdate=December 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=It\u2019s final: BGC belongs to Taguig|last=Punay|first=Edu|url=http://www.philstar.com/metro/2017/11/06/1756019/its-final-bgc-belongs-taguig|newspaper=[[The Philippine Star]]|date=November 6, 2017|accessdate=December 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n{{See also|List of schools in Taguig}}\n[[File:International school manila.gif|right|thumb|International School Manila]]\n[[File:Tupunivlibrary.jpg|left|thumb|Technological University of the Philippines]]\nTaguig City<ref>Taguig city book</ref> is home to several prestigious international schools which provide [[international education]] to Metro Manila residents, such as the [[British School Manila]], [http://www.everestmanila.org// Everest Academy Manila], [[International School Manila]], and [[Manila Japanese School]], which are all located in the University Parkway of Bonifacio Global City. The [[Chinese International School Manila]], [[Enderun Colleges]], and [[Korean International School Philippines]] are in the nearby area of McKinley Hill, while [http://www.beaconschool.ph/ The Beacon School] is located along the nearby [[Chino Roces Avenue]].\n\nOther schools in Fort Bonifacio are the STI College Global City, [[Global City Innovative College]], [[Leaders International Christian School of Manila]] (Christian-based curriculum), Victory Leadership Institute, and [[MGC-New Life Christian Academy]].\n\nTwo of the top state universities are also in Taguig\u2014the [[Polytechnic University of the Philippines]], and the [[Technological University of the Philippines]]. Both universities are located within the city in Central Bicutan and Western Bicutan.\n\nIn 2016, the [[University of the Philippines]] inaugurated its campus in Bonifacio Global City for its law programs.<ref>[https://www.rappler.com/nation/124333-up-bgc-open-2016],</ref> Following that year\nin 2017, the [[De La Salle University College of Law]] opened its Rufino Campus at Bonifacio Global City's University Parkway Drive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/872850/dlsu-inaugurates-law-campus-in-bonifacio-global-city|title=DLSU inaugurates law campus in Bonifacio Global City|first=Jovic|last=Yee|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n[[Enderun Colleges]], an affiliate of Les Roches International School of Hotel Management-Switzerland is an undergraduate college and management school in the Philippines that offers a full range of bachelor's degree and non-degree courses in the fields of international hospitality management and business administration.<ref>https://www.enderuncolleges.com/about/</ref> Likewise, The '''Meridian International College or MINT''', a tertiary educational institution of arts, business and technology are both located in McKinley Hill, Barangay [[Pinagsama]], Taguig City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mintcollege.com/about-us/|title=Our Story|website=MINT College}}</ref>\n\nTaguig City University, the city's local state university located in Central Bicutan started operations in November 2006.<ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/metro/view_article.php?article_id=111607 Taguig University will have own campus in 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222171849/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/metro/view_article.php?article_id=111607 |date=February 22, 2008 }}, newsinfo.inquirer.net; accessed August 10, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe [[Technical Education and Skills Development Authority]] (TESDA) was established through the enactment of \"Technical Education and Skills Development Act of 1994\", which was signed into law by President [[Fidel V. Ramos]]. This Act aims to encourage the full participation of and mobilize the industry, labor, local government units, and technical-vocational institutions in the skills development of the country's human resource. The TESDA complex and facilities are located at the East Service Road of the South Luzon Expressway in Taguig.\n\nThe [https://web.archive.org/web/20110426063952/http://www.ppsc.gov.ph/ Philippine Public Safety College] in [[Fort Bonifacio]] is an educational institution offering undergraduate and graduate programs for the training, human resource development, and continuing education of police, fire and jail personnel.\n\nTaguig has two Islamic educational institutions located in Maharlika Village\u2014the Maharlika Bandara-Inged Integrated School and the Maharlika Village Islamic Madrasa.\n\nOther notable schools in Taguig include the city's Science High Schools [[Taguig Science High School]] in Barangay San Miguel, [[Senator Renato \"Compa\u00f1ero\" Cayetano Memorial Science and Technology High School]] in Ususan, [[Taguig National High School]], a state-owned secondary institution in New Lower Bicutan, the [[Catholic Church]]-owned [[Colegio de Santa Ana]] (formerly Santa Ana Parochial School), [[The Fisher Valley College]], a Christian school in Hagonoy and Pinagsama and [[Saint Francis of Assisi College System]], a Catholic school in Bagumbayan.\n\nTaguig is set to become the new \"university city\" of Metro Manila as new campuses of [[University of the Philippines]] Professional Schools and [[De La Salle University]] are located in Bonifacio Global City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/nation/2015/07/21/1479372/taguig-become-university-city-new-dlsu-campuses|title=Taguig to become 'university city' with new UP, DLSU campuses|last=Frialde|first=Mike|date=2015-07-21|website=[[The Philippine Star]]|access-date=2016-02-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114231509/http://www.philstar.com/nation/2015/07/21/1479372/taguig-become-university-city-new-dlsu-campuses|archive-date=January 14, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Taguig becoming a \u2018University City\u2019|url = http://www.taguig.gov.ph/taguig-becoming-a-university-city/|website = Official Website of The City of Taguig|access-date = 2016-02-01|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people== \n<gallery>\nFile:PIA NEW PROFILE PIC 2.JPG|[[Pia Cayetano]], Senator\nFile:Senator Alan Peter S. Cayetano (cropped).jpg|[[Alan Peter Cayetano]], House Speaker of the Congress\nFile:Bea Alonzo by Ronn Tan, April 2010.png|[[Bea Alonzo]], actress\n</gallery>\n*[[Dante Ti\u00f1ga]], former Associate Justice\n*[[Rene Cayetano]], former Senator\n*[[Felix Y. Manalo]], Iglesia Ni Cristo Preacher\n*[[Lino Cayetano]], TV/movie director, former Congressman, Mayor\n*[[Jamalul Kiram III]], claimant to throne of [[Sultanate of Sulu]]\n*[[Ervic Vijandre]], actor\n*[[Precious Lara Quigaman]], actress and [[Miss International 2005]] titleholder \n*[[Lance Lucido]], Filipino child actor\n*[[Ate Glow|Rene Facunla Humpshire a.k.a. Ate Glow]], Filipino Actor/Commediane/Impersonator \n*[[Lucita Soriano]], actress\n\n;Groups\n*[[Taguig Renegade Drum and Lyre Corps]], 3 time National Drum and Lyre champion\n\n==International relations==\n\n===Diplomatic missions===\nCountries that have set up permanent missions or offices in the city include:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*{{flag|Denmark}}\n*{{flag|Kazakhstan}}\n*{{flag|South Korea}}\n*{{flag|Kuwait}}\n*{{flag|Malaysia}}\n*{{flag|Norway}}\n*{{flag|Oman}}\n*{{flag|Qatar}}\n*{{flag|Senegal}}\n*{{flag|Singapore}}\n*{{flag|United Arab Emirates}}\n*{{flag|United Kingdom}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Sister cities===\nThe local government of Taguig maintains relations with other cities in the Philippines.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Local\n|-\n| [[Bacolod]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/bacolod/local-news/2012/05/11/council-approves-sisterhood-twinning-taguig-220930|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130616061408/http://www.sunstar.com.ph/bacolod/local-news/2012/05/11/council-approves-sisterhood-twinning-taguig-220930|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 16, 2013|title=Council approves sisterhood, twinning with Taguig|newspaper=SunStar|date=May 11, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Iloilo City]]<ref>{{cite news|url = https://news.mb.com.ph/2018/08/26/iloilo-honors-sister-cities/ |title = Iloilo honors sister cities | newspaper = [[Manila Bulletin]] | date = August 26, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Tabaco]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tabacocity.com.ph/Updates/Resolutions.php?id=332|title=RESOLUTION EXPRESSING INTENTION FOR SISTERHOOD AND TWINNING WITH TAGUIG CITY|newspaper=Tabaco City.com|date=March 21, 2011|access-date=May 14, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029212053/http://www.tabacocity.com.ph/Updates/Resolutions.php?id=332|archive-date=October 29, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Vigan]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vigancitycouncil.com.ph/files/resolutions/Sisterhood%20Resolutions.pdf|title=A RESOLUTION EXTENDING AN INVITATION TO THE CITY OF TAGUIG TO  BECOME A SISTER CITY OF VIGAN, ILOCOS SUR|newspaper=City of Vigan|date=February 18, 2008}}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!International\n|-\n| {{flagdeco|AUS}} [[Blacktown]], Australia<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.dfa.gov.ph/dfa-news/news-from-our-foreign-service-postsupdate/16102-taguig-mayor-lani-cayetano-forges-links-with-mayor-stephen-bali-of-blacktown-city-in-australia |title = Taguig Mayor Lani Cayetano Forges Links with Mayor Stephen Bali of Blacktown City in Australia | newspaper = DFA.gov.ph | date = March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Philippines}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Taguig}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111015011952/http://www.taguig.gov.ph/ Official Website of Taguig]\n*[http://www.thinkbigtaguig.com/ Think Big Taguig - Official Lifestyle Website]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/taguigcity Official Facebook page of City of Taguig]\n*[http://www.bonifacioglobalcity.com.ph Bonifacio Global City]\n*{{OSM relation|184776}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n| North     = [[Pateros, Metro Manila|Pateros]] / [[Pasig]]\n| West      = [[Pasay]]<br>[[Para\u00f1aque]]\n| Center    = Taguig\n| East      = ''[[Laguna de Bay]]''\n| South     = [[Muntinlupa]]\n| Northwest = [[Makati]]\n| Northeast = [[Cainta, Rizal]]<br>[[Taytay, Rizal]]\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Articles related to Taguig\n| list  =\n{{Taguig}}\n{{Metro Manila}}\n{{Philippine cities}}\n{{Largest cities of the Philippines}}\n{{Most populous cities in Philippines}}\n{{Largest Cities and Municipalities in Luzon}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Taguig| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1587]]\n[[Category:1587 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Pasig River]]\n[[Category:Populated places on Laguna de Bay]]\n", "name_user": "Uzume", "label": "safe", "comment": "defaults to the current QID", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taguig"}
{"title_page": "Henri Cole", "text_new": "{{short description|American poet|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n\n'''Henri Cole''' (born 1956) is an [[American poetry|American]] [[poet]], who has published many collections of poetry and a memoir. His books have been translated into French, Spanish, Italian, German, and Arabic.\n\n{{Infobox person\n| image     = Henri_Cole_.jpg\n| birth_date    = May 9, 1956\n| birth_place   = Fukuoka, Japan\n| occupation    = Poet\n}}\n\n==Biography==\nHenri Cole was born in [[Fukuoka, Fukuoka|Fukuoka]], [[Japan]], to an American father and [[Armenians in France|French-Armenian]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3692/is_200405/ai_n9401647/print |first=Christopher |last=Lydon |title=Out of Yearning, Order: Henri Cole's poetry |publisher=The Huffington Post |date=December 2009 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> mother, and raised in [[Virginia]], [[United States]].  His father, a North Carolinian, enlisted in the service after graduating from high school and, while stationed in [[Marseilles]], met Cole's mother, who worked at the PX.  Together they lived in [[Japan]], [[Germany]], [[Illinois]], [[California]], [[Nevada, Missouri]] and [[Virginia]], where Cole attended public schools and [[the College of William and Mary]].  He has published ten collections of poetry in English.\n\nFrom 1982 until 1988 he was executive director of The [[Academy of American Poets]].<ref>http://www.poets.org/poetsorg/poet/henri-cole</ref> \nSince that time he has held many teaching positions and been artist-in-residence at various institutions, including [[Brandeis University]], [[Columbia University]], [[Davidson College]], [[Harvard University]], [[Ohio State University]], [[Reed College]], [[Smith College]], [[The College of William and Mary]], and [[Yale University]].  He has collaborated with the visual artists Jenny Holzer and Kiki Smith.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jenny Holzer collaborations|url=http://www.art21.org/texts/jenny-holzer/interview-jenny-holzer-collaborating-with-poet-henri-cole|website=art21.org|publisher=Art21|accessdate=26 April 2015}}</ref>  And from 2010 to 2014, he was poetry editor of [[The New Republic]].  Cole currently teaches at [[Claremont McKenna College]].\n\n==Books of poetry==\n* 2020: ''Blizzard'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=Blizzard|url=https://us.macmillan.com/books/9780374114381|website=Macmillan|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2015: ''Nothing to Declare'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=Nothing to Declare|url=http://us.macmillan.com/nothingtodeclare/henricole|website=Macmillan|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015: ''Le Merle, Le Loup suivi de Toucher'' (French translation by Claire Malroux), Paris: Le bruit du temps<ref>{{cite web|title=Le Merle, Le Loup|url=http://www.lebruitdutemps.fr/_auteurs/Cole/HenriCole.htm|website=Le bruit du temps|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2011: ''Touch'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=Touch|url=http://us.macmillan.com/author/henricole|website=Macmillan|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2011: ''Terre M\u00e9diane'' (French translation by Claire Malroux), Paris: Le bruit du temps<ref>{{cite web|title=Terre Mediane|url=http://www.lebruitdutemps.fr/_auteurs/Cole/HenriCole.htm|website=Le bruit du temps|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''Mirlo y Lobo'' (Spanish translation by Eduardo L\u00f3pez Truco), Cantabria: Qu\u00e1lea Editorial<ref>{{cite web|title=Mirlo y Lobo|url=http://www.culturamas.es/blog/2010/12/18/mirlo-y-lobo-de-henri-cole-qualea-editorial/|website=Culturamas|publisher=Culturamas|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''Autoritratto con Gatti'' (Italian translation by Massimo Bacigalupo), Parma: Guanda Editore<ref>{{cite web|title=Autoitratto con Gatti|url=http://www.guanda.it/scheda.asp?editore=Guanda&idlibro=6993&titolo=AUTORITRATTO+CON+GATTI|website=Guanda Editore|publisher=Guanda Editore|access-date=2015-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924024032/http://www.guanda.it/scheda.asp?editore=Guanda&idlibro=6993&titolo=AUTORITRATTO+CON+GATTI|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''Pierce the Skin (Selected Poems, 1982-2007)'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=Pierce the Skin|url=http://us.macmillan.com/author/henricole|website=Macmillan|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2008: ''La Apariencia de la Cosas'' (Spanish translation by Eduardo L\u00f3pez Truco), Cantabria: Qu\u00e1lea Editorial<ref>{{cite web|title=La Apariencia de la Cosas|url=http://www.casadellibro.com/libro-la-apariencia-de-las-cosas-antologia-poetica/9788493690908/1252431|website=Casa del Libro|publisher=Casa del Libro|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2007: ''Blackbird and Wolf'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=Blackbird and Wolf|url=http://us.macmillan.com/blackbirdandwolf/henricole|website=Macmillan|publisher=Macmillan|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2005: ''Vingt-Deux Po\u00e8mes'' (French translation by Claire Malroux), Paris: Yvon Lambert<ref>{{cite web|title=Vingt-Deux Poems|url=http://www.lespressesdureel.com/EN/ouvrage.php?id=1303&menu=|website=lesoressesdureel.com|publisher=Les presses du reel|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2003: ''Middle Earth'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=Middle Earth|url=http://us.macmillan.com/middleearth/henricole|website=Macmillan|publisher=Macmillan|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 1998: ''The Visible Man'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=The Visible Man|url=http://us.macmillan.com/thevisibleman/henricole|website=Macmillan|publisher=Macmillan}}</ref>\n* 1995: ''The Look of Things''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Look of Things|url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Look-Things-Henri-Cole/dp/067943352X|website=amazon.com|publisher=amazon|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 1989: ''The Zoo Wheel of Knowledge''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Zoo Wheel of Knowledge|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/150311.The_Zoo_Wheel_of_Knowledge|website=goodreads.com|publisher=Good Reads|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 1986: ''The Marble Queen''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Marble Queen|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/824641.The_Marble_Queen|website=goodreads.com|publisher=Good Reads|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Books of prose ==\n* 2020: \u0628\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0631\u0641\u064a\u0651\u0629: \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0651\u064a\u0627\u062d\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0628\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0633  (''Orphic Paris'', Arabic translation by Amani Lazar), United Arab Emirates: Rewayat Books<ref>{{cite web|title=Orphic Paris|url=https://www.kalimatgroup.ae/en/orphic-paris.html|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>  \n* 2018: ''Orphic Paris'', New York, New York Review Books<ref>{{cite web|title=Orphic Paris|url=https://www.nyrb.com/products/orphic-paris?variant=53435509063|website=New York Review Books|accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n* 2018: ''Paris-Orph\u00e9e  ''(French translation by Claire Malroux), Paris: Le bruit du temps<ref>{{cite web|title=Paris-Orph\u00e9e|url=http://www.lebruitdutemps.fr/_auteurs/Cole/HenriCole.htm|website=Le bruit du temps|accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* 2017 &mdash; [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]], Elected Member\n* 2016 &mdash; [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]], Award of Merit Medal in Poetry<ref>{{cite web|title=American Academy of Arts and Letters|url=http://www.artsandletters.org/press_releases/2016literature.pdf|website=American Academy of Arts and Letters|accessdate=15 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417205340/http://www.artsandletters.org/press_releases/2016literature.pdf|archivedate=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n* 2014 &mdash; [[Radcliffe Institute]] for Advanced Study at Harvard, Fellow<ref>{{cite web|title=Fellow|url=http://www.radcliffe.harvard.edu/people/henri-cole|website=Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study|publisher=Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2012 &mdash; The [[Thom Gunn Award]] for Poetry for ''Touch'',<ref>{{Cite web|title=\"Publishing Triangle Winners Unveiled\", ''GalleyCat'', 04/20/2012|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/galleycat/publishing-triangle-winners-unveiled_b50462}}</ref> Publishing Triangle\n* 2012 &mdash; [[Jackson Poetry Prize|The Jackson Poetry Prize]] for ''Touch'', Poets & Writers<ref>{{cite web|title=Jackson Poetry Prize|url=http://www.pw.org/about-us/jackson_poetry_prize|website=Poets & Writers|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2011 &mdash; Harvard University [[Phi Beta Kappa]] poet<ref>{{cite web|title=Phi Beta Kappa Poet|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2011/05/henri-cole-joyce-carol-oates-phi-beta-kappa|website=Harvard Magazine|publisher=Harvard Magazine|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2011 &mdash; Finalist, [[Los Angeles Times Book Award]] in Poetry for ''Pierce the Skin (Selected Poems 1982-2007)''<ref>{{cite web|title=LA Times Book Award|url=http://events.latimes.com/bookprizes/previous-winners/year-2010/|website=events.latimes.com|publisher=LA Times|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2010 &mdash; [[American Academy of Arts & Sciences]], elected member<ref>{{cite web|title=Academy of Arts and Sciences|url=https://www.amacad.org/multimedia/pdfs/alphalist.pdf|website=amacad.org|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2009 &mdash; Sara Teasdale Award in Poetry, Wellesley College\n* 2009 &mdash; [[National Endowment for the Arts]] Literature Fellowship \n* 2008 &mdash; [[Lenore Marshall Poetry Prize]] for ''Blackbird and Wolf'', Academy of American Poets<ref>{{cite web|title=Lenore Marshall Poetry Prize|url=http://www.poets.org/academy-american-poets/prizes/lenore-marshall-poetry-prize|website=poets.org|publisher=Academy of American Poets|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref> \n* 2008 &mdash; [[Ambassador Book Award]] in Poetry for ''Blackbird and Wolf'', English-Speaking Union of the United States<ref>[[Ambassador Book Award]]</ref>\n* 2008 &mdash; [[Massachusetts Book Award]] in Poetry for ''Blackbird and Wolf''<ref>{{cite web|title=Massachusetts Book Award|url=https://www.yumpu.com/en/document/view/29815615/press-release-massachusetts-center-for-the-book|website=yumpu.com|publisher=Massachusetts Center for the Book|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2008 &mdash; [[Lambda Literary Award]] in Poetry for ''Blackbird and Wolf''<ref>{{cite web|title=Lambda Literary Award|url=http://www.lambdaliterary.org/winners-finalists/04/30/lambda-literary-awards-2007-2/#lgbtpoetry|website=lambdaliterary.org|publisher=Lambda Literary Awards|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2007 &mdash; [[United States Artists]] USA Hildreth/Williams Fellow, Literature<ref>{{cite web|title=United States Artists Fellowship|url=http://www.unitedstatesartists.org/fellows//henri-cole|website=unitedstatesartists.org|publisher=United States Artists|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2004 &mdash; [[Kingsley Tufts Poetry Award]] for ''Middle Earth''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3692/is_200405/ai_n9401647/print |first=Christopher |last=Hennessy |title=An Interview by Christopher Hennessy |publisher=American Poetry Review |date=May 2005 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref>\n* 2004 &mdash; [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation]] Fellowship<ref>{{cite web|title=Guggenheim Fellowship|url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/henri-cole/|website=gf.org|publisher=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation}}</ref>\n* 2004 &mdash; Award in Literature, [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Award in Literature|url=http://www.artsandletters.org/press_releases/2004literature.php|website=artsandletters.org|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Letters|accessdate=16 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416214402/http://www.artsandletters.org/press_releases/2004literature.php|archivedate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2004 &mdash; Finalist, [[Pulitzer Prize]] in Poetry for ''Middle Earth''<ref>{{cite web|title=Pulitzer|url=http://www.pulitzer.org/bycat/Poetry|website=pulitzer.org|publisher=Pulitzer|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2004 &mdash; Finalist, [[Los Angeles Times Book Award]] in Poetry for '' Middle Earth''<ref>{{cite web|title=LA Times Book Award|url=http://events.latimes.com/bookprizes/press-releases/2004-03-09/|website=events.latimes.com|publisher=LA Times|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150922082938/http://events.latimes.com/bookprizes/press-releases/2004-03-09/|archivedate=2015-09-22}}</ref>\n* 2004 &mdash; [[Massachusetts Book Award]] in Poetry for ''Middle Earth''<ref>{{cite web|title=Massachusetts Book Award|url=http://www.bpl.org/research/adultbooklists/massbookawards04.htm|website=bpl.org|publisher=Boston Public Library|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2001 &mdash; Japan-US Friendship Commission, Creative Artist Fellowship<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan Fellowship|url=http://www.jusfc.gov/grant_program/biennial-reports/2001-2002-biennial-report/|website=jusfc.gov|publisher=Japan-United States Friendship Commission|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2000 &mdash; [[Berlin Prize]], [[American Academy in Berlin]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Berlin Prize|url=http://www.americanacademy.de/home/alumni/alumni-directory?page=1|website=americanacademy.de|publisher=American Academy in Berlin|accessdate=16 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416164717/http://www.americanacademy.de/home/alumni/alumni-directory?page=1|archivedate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 1995 &mdash; [[Rome Prize]] in Literature, American Academy of Arts and Letters<ref>{{cite web|title=Rome Prize|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/22/arts/rome-prize-winners-are-announced.html|website=nytimes.com|publisher=American Academy in Rome}}</ref>\n* 1993 &mdash; [[National Endowment for the Arts]] Literature Fellowship<ref>{{cite web|title=NEA Fellowship|url=http://arts.gov/sites/default/files/NEA_lit.pdf|website=arts.gov|publisher=National Endowment for the Arts}}</ref>\n* 1989 &mdash; [[Amy Lowell Poetry Travelling Scholarship]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Amy Lowell Poetry Travelling Scholarship|url=http://www.amylowell.org/past_recipients.htm|website=amylowell.org|publisher=Choate, Hall & Stewart|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 1985 &mdash; [[Ingram Merrill Foundation]] Award (also 1990)<ref>[[Ingram Merrill Foundation]]</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nCole is openly gay, though in his early work he turned to \"nature as a mask for writing about private feelings.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/6312/henri-cole-the-art-of-poetry-no-98-henri-cole|title=Henri Cole, The Art of Poetry No. 98|last=Weiss|first=Sasha|date=2014|work=The Paris Review|access-date=2018-04-11|issue=209|volume=Summer 2014|language=en|issn=0031-2037}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://henricole.com/ Official website]\n* [http://www.poets.org/poet.php/prmPID/1083 Academy of American Poets -- Henri Cole's webpage]\n* Twitter -- @ColeHenri\n* [http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/20964 THE NATION -- \"The Art of Violent Concision\"]\n* [http://www.tnr.com/book/review/making-soul THE NEW REPUBLIC -- \"Making a Soul\"]\n* [http://www.randomhouse.com/knopf/authors/cole/poetsonpoetry.html A personal essay:  \"How I Grew\"]\n* [http://www.poetrysociety.org/psa/poetry/crossroads/qa_american_poetry/henri_cole/  An interview:  \"What is American about American poetry\"]\n* [http://www.oxonianreview.org/wp/say-all-i-need-to-say-better/ 'All I need to Say, Better'], review of ''Pierce the Skin'' in the ''[[Oxonian Review]]''\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/6312/the-art-of-poetry-no-98-henri-cole|title=Henri Cole, The Art of Poetry, The Paris Review, Summer 2014, No. 98(with Sasha Weiss)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cole, Henri}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:American writers of Armenian descent]]\n[[Category:Columbia University staff]]\n[[Category:Harvard University staff]]\n[[Category:College of William & Mary alumni]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Smith College faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lambda Literary Award winners]]\n[[Category:Berlin Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:LGBT poets]]\n[[Category:Gay academics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American poet|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n\n'''Henri Cole''' (born 1956) is an [[American poetry|American]] [[poet]], who has published many collections of poetry and a memoir. His books have been translated into French, Spanish, Italian, Arabic, and German.\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Henri Cole\n| birth_date    = May 9, 1956\n| birth_place   = Fukuoka, Japan\n| occupation    = Poet\n}}\n\n==Biography==\nHenri Cole was born in [[Fukuoka, Fukuoka|Fukuoka]], [[Japan]], to an American father and [[Armenians in France|French-Armenian]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3692/is_200405/ai_n9401647/print |first=Christopher |last=Lydon |title=Out of Yearning, Order: Henri Cole's poetry |publisher=The Huffington Post |date=December 2009 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> mother, and raised in [[Virginia]], [[United States]].  His father, a North Carolinian, enlisted in the service after graduating from high school and, while stationed in [[Marseilles]], met Cole's mother, who worked at the PX.  Together they lived in [[Japan]], [[Germany]], [[Illinois]], [[California]], [[Nevada, Missouri]] and [[Virginia]], where Cole attended public schools and [[the College of William and Mary]].  He has published ten collections of poetry in English.\n\nFrom 1982 until 1988 he was executive director of The [[Academy of American Poets]].<ref>http://www.poets.org/poetsorg/poet/henri-cole</ref> \nSince that time he has held many teaching positions and been artist-in-residence at various institutions, including [[Brandeis University]], [[Columbia University]], [[Davidson College]], [[Harvard University]], [[Ohio State University]], [[Reed College]], [[Smith College]], [[The College of William and Mary]], and [[Yale University]].  He has collaborated with the visual artists Jenny Holzer and Kiki Smith.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jenny Holzer collaborations|url=http://www.art21.org/texts/jenny-holzer/interview-jenny-holzer-collaborating-with-poet-henri-cole|website=art21.org|publisher=Art21|accessdate=26 April 2015}}</ref>  And from 2010 to 2014, he was poetry editor of [[The New Republic]].  Cole currently teaches at [[Claremont McKenna College]].\n\n==Books of poetry==\n* 2020: ''Blizzard'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=Blizzard|url=https://us.macmillan.com/books/9780374114381|website=Macmillan|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2015: ''Nothing to Declare'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=Nothing to Declare|url=http://us.macmillan.com/nothingtodeclare/henricole|website=Macmillan|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015: ''Le Merle, Le Loup suivi de Toucher'' (French translation by Claire Malroux), Paris: Le bruit du temps<ref>{{cite web|title=Le Merle, Le Loup|url=http://www.lebruitdutemps.fr/_auteurs/Cole/HenriCole.htm|website=Le bruit du temps|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2011: ''Touch'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=Touch|url=http://us.macmillan.com/author/henricole|website=Macmillan|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2011: ''Terre M\u00e9diane'' (French translation by Claire Malroux), Paris: Le bruit du temps<ref>{{cite web|title=Terre Mediane|url=http://www.lebruitdutemps.fr/_auteurs/Cole/HenriCole.htm|website=Le bruit du temps|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''Mirlo y Lobo'' (Spanish translation by Eduardo L\u00f3pez Truco), Cantabria: Qu\u00e1lea Editorial<ref>{{cite web|title=Mirlo y Lobo|url=http://www.culturamas.es/blog/2010/12/18/mirlo-y-lobo-de-henri-cole-qualea-editorial/|website=Culturamas|publisher=Culturamas|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''Autoritratto con Gatti'' (Italian translation by Massimo Bacigalupo), Parma: Guanda Editore<ref>{{cite web|title=Autoitratto con Gatti|url=http://www.guanda.it/scheda.asp?editore=Guanda&idlibro=6993&titolo=AUTORITRATTO+CON+GATTI|website=Guanda Editore|publisher=Guanda Editore|access-date=2015-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924024032/http://www.guanda.it/scheda.asp?editore=Guanda&idlibro=6993&titolo=AUTORITRATTO+CON+GATTI|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''Pierce the Skin (Selected Poems, 1982-2007)'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=Pierce the Skin|url=http://us.macmillan.com/author/henricole|website=Macmillan|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2008: ''La Apariencia de la Cosas'' (Spanish translation by Eduardo L\u00f3pez Truco), Cantabria: Qu\u00e1lea Editorial<ref>{{cite web|title=La Apariencia de la Cosas|url=http://www.casadellibro.com/libro-la-apariencia-de-las-cosas-antologia-poetica/9788493690908/1252431|website=Casa del Libro|publisher=Casa del Libro|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2007: ''Blackbird and Wolf'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=Blackbird and Wolf|url=http://us.macmillan.com/blackbirdandwolf/henricole|website=Macmillan|publisher=Macmillan|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2005: ''Vingt-Deux Po\u00e8mes'' (French translation by Claire Malroux), Paris: Yvon Lambert<ref>{{cite web|title=Vingt-Deux Poems|url=http://www.lespressesdureel.com/EN/ouvrage.php?id=1303&menu=|website=lesoressesdureel.com|publisher=Les presses du reel|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2003: ''Middle Earth'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=Middle Earth|url=http://us.macmillan.com/middleearth/henricole|website=Macmillan|publisher=Macmillan|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 1998: ''The Visible Man'', New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux<ref>{{cite web|title=The Visible Man|url=http://us.macmillan.com/thevisibleman/henricole|website=Macmillan|publisher=Macmillan}}</ref>\n* 1995: ''The Look of Things''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Look of Things|url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Look-Things-Henri-Cole/dp/067943352X|website=amazon.com|publisher=amazon|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 1989: ''The Zoo Wheel of Knowledge''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Zoo Wheel of Knowledge|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/150311.The_Zoo_Wheel_of_Knowledge|website=goodreads.com|publisher=Good Reads|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 1986: ''The Marble Queen''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Marble Queen|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/824641.The_Marble_Queen|website=goodreads.com|publisher=Good Reads|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Books of prose ==\n* 2020: \u0628\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0631\u0641\u064a\u0651\u0629: \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0651\u064a\u0627\u062d\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0628\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0633  (''Orphic Paris'', Arabic translation by Amani Lazar), United Arab Emirates: Rewayat Books<ref>{{cite web|title=Orphic Paris|url=https://www.kalimatgroup.ae/en/orphic-paris.html|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>  \n* 2018: ''Orphic Paris'', New York, New York Review Books<ref>{{cite web|title=Orphic Paris|url=https://www.nyrb.com/products/orphic-paris?variant=53435509063|website=New York Review Books|accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n* 2018: ''Paris-Orph\u00e9e  ''(French translation by Claire Malroux), Paris: Le bruit du temps<ref>{{cite web|title=Paris-Orph\u00e9e|url=http://www.lebruitdutemps.fr/_auteurs/Cole/HenriCole.htm|website=Le bruit du temps|accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* 2017 &mdash; [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]], Elected Member\n* 2016 &mdash; [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]